title: Football: Greenland tops Marshall, stays unbeaten
text:
By Brandon Howard Posted: October 17, 2015 at 1 a.m. 
GREENLAND -- Cole Self and Alex Sisemore combined for six touchdowns to lead Greenland to a 39-18 win over Marshall on Friday night at Jonathan Ramey Memorial Field. 
Greenland (7-0, 4-0 3A-1) started slow on offense against a scrappy Marshall (1-6, 0-4) defense. But the Pirates exploded for 18 points in the second quarter thanks to scoring drives of 53, 33 and 45 yards.

Sisemore carried the ball 30 times for 198 yards and two touchdowns. Self was a model of efficiency through the air, completing 9 of 14 passes for 141 yards and three touchdowns. Self added a 23-yard rushing touchdown in the third quarter. 
Despite the victory, Greenland coach Lee Larkan said he wants to see a better effort from his team. 
"You're always happy win you win," Larkan said. "Marshall got after us and had a great scheme. But we played like we practiced; we've got to try to get better." 
Greenland has beaten opponents by an average of 27.3 points, and the Pirates hadn't allowed a score in 13 consecutive quarters. The streak ended in the second quarter when Marshall's Tyler Magness found a hole and raced 59 yards for a touchdown. 
Marshall scored twice in the second half. Bobcats quarterback Andrew Phillips connected with Trey Kelley for a 22-yard touchdown pass on fourth down. With time winding down in regulation, Kendrick Campbell barrelled into the end zone from the 2-yard line. 
"I'm real proud of (ending Greenland's scoreless streak)," Marshall coach Lee Sadler said. "We only brought 17 guys tonight and we're banged up." 
With the season winding down, Sadler said he hopes to build on the momentum from the Bobcats' solid outing against Greenland.
